{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17623978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17623978"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:14:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:14:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16885"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16885","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16885"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.73,0.04,0,0.23,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9575"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67515"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9575"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16885"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52967"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4903"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"6641"},{"type":"tags","id":"9858"},{"type":"tags","id":"9860"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22601"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22625"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67515"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EVentricular diastole consists of four distinct phases: isovolumetric relaxation, rapid filling, diastasis, and atrial contraction. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the sequence of events during the rapid filling phase of diastole?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Atrioventricular valves open and ventricles fill due to pressure gradient","All heart valves close and ventricular pressure falls","Atrial and ventricular pressures equalise with minimal flow","Atrial contraction forces additional blood into ventricles","Semilunar valves open and blood exits ventricles"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eatrioventricular valves open and ventricles fill due to pressure gradient\u003C/strong\u003E during the rapid filling phase. This occurs when ventricular pressure falls below atrial pressure after isovolumetric relaxation, creating a large pressure gradient that drives rapid ventricular filling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options describe other phases:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAll heart valves close and ventricular pressure falls\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes isovolumetric relaxation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtrial and ventricular pressures equalise with minimal flow\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes diastasis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtrial contraction forces additional blood into ventricles\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes atrial systole/atrial kick\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESemilunar valves open and blood exits ventricles\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the beginning of ventricular systole\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe rapid filling phase accounts for approximately 70-80% of ventricular filling and is crucial for optimal cardiac function. It ends when the pressure gradient between atria and ventricles decreases, leading to diastasis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ventricular diastole consists of four phases: isovolumetric relaxation, rapid filling, diastasis, and atrial contraction.","The rapid filling phase occurs immediately after isovolumetric relaxation when the atrioventricular valves open.","The pressure gradient between atria and ventricles is highest during rapid filling, allowing 70-80% of ventricular filling to occur during this phase."],"references":["Boron WF, Boulpaep EL. Medical physiology. 3rd ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2017."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52967"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16885"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52967"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-05T16:20:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-05T16:23:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9575"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67515"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/